<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-calculus-of-power-series"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Calculus of Power Series</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Inside the interval of convergence, power series behave much like
      polynomials. In particular, they can be differentiated and integrated
      term by term. The full proof uses ideas about uniform convergence, but
      the behavior of the new coefficients is already visible from the root
      test.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-derived-integrated-power-series-radius">
    <title>Derived and Integrated Series Have the Same Radius</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the power series
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(x-x_0)^n
        </me>
        has radius of convergence <m>R</m>. Then the formal derivative
        <me>
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty na_n(x-x_0)^{n-1}
        </me>
        and the formal integral
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{a_n}{n+1}(x-x_0)^{n+1}
        </me>
        also have radius of convergence <m>R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          L=\limsup |a_n|^{1/n},
        </me>
        so that <m>R=1/L</m> by <xref ref="thm-radius-of-convergence"/>.
        Since <m>n^{1/n}\to 1</m> by <xref ref="eg-nth-root-of-n"/>, we have
        <me>
          \limsup |na_n|^{1/n}
          =
          \limsup n^{1/n}|a_n|^{1/n}
          =
          L.
        </me>
        Hence the formal derivative has radius <m>R</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Likewise, because <m>(n+1)^{1/n}\to 1</m>,
        <me>
          \limsup \left|\frac{a_n}{n+1}\right|^{1/n}
          =
          \limsup \frac{|a_n|^{1/n}}{(n+1)^{1/n}}
          =
          L,
        </me>
        so the formal integral also has radius <m>R</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-termwise-calculus-power-series">
    <title>Term-by-Term Differentiation and Integration</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose
        <me>
          f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(x-x_0)^n
        </me>
        has radius of convergence <m>R&gt;0</m>. Then on the interval
        <m>(x_0-R,x_0+R)</m> the function <m>f</m> is differentiable and has
        antiderivatives. Moreover,
        <me>
          f'(x)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty na_n(x-x_0)^{n-1}
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          \int_{x_0}^x f(t)\,dt
          =
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{a_n}{n+1}(x-x_0)^{n+1}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We omit the proof. It uses uniform convergence on closed subintervals
        of <m>(x_0-R,x_0+R)</m>. The previous proposition already shows that
        the differentiated and integrated series have the same radius of
        convergence.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-power-series-sum-n-over-two-power-n">
    <statement>
      <p>
        We can compute the sum
        <me>
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{2^n}.
        </me>
        By the geometric series formula (<xref ref="prop-geometric-series"/>),
        <me>
          \frac{1}{1-x}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
        Differentiating term by term gives
        <me>
          \frac{1}{(1-x)^2}
          =
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty nx^{n-1}.
        </me>
        Multiplying by <m>x</m>, we obtain
        <me>
          \frac{x}{(1-x)^2}
          =
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty nx^n.
        </me>
        Evaluating at <m>x=1/2</m> gives
        <me>
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{2^n}
          =
          \frac{\frac12}{(1-\frac12)^2}
          =
          2.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="eg-power-series-log-and-arctan">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The geometric series also yields familiar expansions. Replacing
        <m>x</m> by <m>-x</m>, we get
        <me>
          \frac{1}{1+x}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n x^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
        Integrating from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          \ln(1+x)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}x^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Likewise,
        <me>
          \frac{1}{1+x^2}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n x^{2n}
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1,
        </me>
        so integrating from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> yields
        <me>
          \arctan x
          =
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{2n+1}x^{2n+1}
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-abel-power-series">
    <title>Abel's Theorem on Power Series</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n
        </me>
        be a power series with radius of convergence <m>1</m>. If the series
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n
        </me>
        converges to <m>L</m>, then
        <me>
          \lim_{x\to 1^-} f(x)=L.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Replacing <m>a_0</m> by <m>a_0-L</m>, we may assume without loss of
        generality that <m>L=0</m>. Let
        <me>
          s_k:=\sum_{n=0}^k a_n.
        </me>
        Then <m>s_k \to 0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For <m>|x|&lt;1</m>, the geometric series
        <m>\sum_{m=0}^\infty x^m</m> converges absolutely by
        <xref ref="prop-geometric-series"/>. Hence Mertens' theorem
        (<xref ref="thm-mertens-series"/>) applies to the product of
        <m>\sum_{m=0}^\infty x^m</m> and <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n</m>, and
        gives
        <me>
          \frac{f(x)}{1-x}
          =
          \left(\sum_{m=0}^\infty x^m\right)\left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n\right)
          =
          \sum_{k=0}^\infty s_kx^k.
        </me>
        Therefore
        <me>
          f(x)=(1-x)\sum_{k=0}^\infty s_kx^k
          \qquad \text{for } 0&lt;x&lt;1.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>. Since <m>s_k \to 0</m>, there exists
        <m>N</m> such that <m>|s_k|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>k \ge N</m>.
        Then for <m>0&lt;x&lt;1</m>,
        <me>
          \left|(1-x)\sum_{k=N}^\infty s_kx^k\right|
          \le
          (1-x)\sum_{k=N}^\infty |s_k|x^k
          \lt
          \varepsilon(1-x)\sum_{k=N}^\infty x^k
          =
          \varepsilon x^N
          \le
          \varepsilon.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        For the remaining finitely many terms, let
        <me>
          B:=\max\{|s_0|,|s_1|,\dots,|s_{N-1}|\}.
        </me>
        Then
        <me>
          \left|(1-x)\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} s_kx^k\right|
          \le
          B(1-x)\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} x^k
          =
          B(1-x^N).
        </me>
        Since <m>1-x^N \to 0</m> as <m>x \to 1^-</m>, there exists
        <m>\delta&gt;0</m> such that
        <m>0&lt;1-x&lt;\delta</m> implies <m>B(1-x^N)&lt;\varepsilon</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Combining the two estimates, we obtain <m>|f(x)|&lt;2\varepsilon</m>
        whenever <m>0&lt;1-x&lt;\delta</m>. Thus
        <m>\lim_{x\to 1^-} f(x)=0</m>. Undoing the initial reduction proves
        that <m>\lim_{x\to 1^-} f(x)=L</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    By a simple change of variables, Abel's theorem also applies at either
    endpoint of a finite interval of convergence.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-abel-ln2">
    <statement>
      <p>
        From <xref ref="eg-power-series-log-and-arctan"/>, we know that
        <me>
          \ln(1+x)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}x^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
        The series at <m>x=1</m> is the alternating harmonic series, which
        converges by <xref ref="prop-alternating-series-test"/>. Since
        <m>\ln(1+x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=1</m>, Abel's theorem gives
        <me>
          \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}
          =
          \lim_{x\to 1^-}\ln(1+x)
          =
          \ln 2.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    These examples illustrate a general principle: once a single power series
    is known, algebraic manipulations together with differentiation and
    integration often produce many others.
  </p>
</section>
